# KDP Listing — {BOOK TITLE}

Copy-paste blocks for the Amazon KDP "Book Details" and related screens.
HTML tags supported by KDP: `<b> <i> <u> <h4> <h5> <h6> <br> <p> <ul>
<ol> <li>`. Each block is under KDP's character limits.

---

## TITLE FIELDS

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| **Book title** | `{TITLE}` |
| **Subtitle** | `{SUBTITLE / TAGLINE}` |
| **Series name** | *(leave blank for standalone or first-in-series until book 2 ships)* |
| **Edition number** | `1` |
| **Author** | `{AUTHOR}` |

---

## BOOK DESCRIPTION (4,000 char max)

Paste into the "Description" field on KDP. Target length: 2,500-3,500 chars
including HTML. Structure:

1. One-line author credibility hook (italic h5 of past credentials)
2. ALL-CAPS hero tagline (the line you want on a Times Square billboard)
3. Two short paragraphs establishing the protagonist and the stakes
4. One sentence summarizing the world (geography, antagonist, premise)
5. Two-sentence escalation paragraph (the threat)
6. Pull-quoted gut-punch line
7. Comp-titles list ("Perfect for fans of: ...")
8. Closing emotional hook

```html
<h4>{Optional author credibility — past bestselling work, awards, "Most X by Y", etc.}</h4>

<h5>"{Optional notable quote about the author}" — <i>{Source}</i></h5>

<p><b>{ALL-CAPS HERO TAGLINE.}</b></p>

<p>{Open with one concrete sentence that drops the reader into the
protagonist's normal life. End with the inciting incident.}</p>

<p>{Establish who the protagonist is in two sentences. End with the
"is not the man you send to do this — which is exactly why..."
turn that sets up why THIS protagonist is the right one.}</p>

<p><b>{Until now. / But this time. / Two-word tilt sentence.}</b></p>

<p>{One sentence that names the world / antagonist / geography / scope.
Should make the reader feel the size of the book.}</p>

<p>{Two-sentence escalation. End with leverage on something the reader
cares about — kids, a deadline, a betrayal.}</p>

<p><b>{Three-beat tagline, e.g., "Four pieces of proof. Four cities.
One impossible truth."}</b></p>

<p>{One closing sentence that names the stakes in concrete time —
"And forty-eight hours to live." / "And the fight starts at dawn."}</p>

<h5>Perfect for fans of:</h5>
<ul>
<li>{COMP AUTHOR}'s <i>{COMP TITLE}</i></li>
<li>{COMP AUTHOR}'s <i>{COMP TITLE}</i></li>
<li>{COMP AUTHOR}'s <i>{COMP TITLE}</i></li>
</ul>

<p><b>{Final gut-punch line — the one quote you want on the back cover.}</b></p>

<p><i>{Closing italic — "The hunt begins." / "The reckoning starts here." / "Read at your own risk."}</i></p>
```

